06396nam a22007335i 9780822386872DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223868727 a10.1515/97808223868722doi  a(DE-B1597)553379  a(OCoLC)1154662093  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS113b.P35 2005 7aSOC0020102bisacsh00aPalestine, Israel, and the Politics of Popular Culture /cRebecca L. Stein, Ted Swedenburg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (424 p.) :b19 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Popular Culture, Transnationality, and Radical History -- tI HISTORICAL ARTICULATIONS -- tWasif Jawhariyyeh, Popular Music, and Early Modernity in Jerusalem -- tThe Palestinian Press in Mandatory Jaffa: Advertising, Nationalism, and the Public Sphere -- tPost-Zionism and Its Popular Cultures -- tII CINEMAS AND CYBERSPACES -- tCross/Cast: Passing in Israeli and Palestinian Cinema -- tVirtual Nation: Palestinian Cyberculture in Lebanese Camps -- tIs There a Palestinian Cinema? The National and Transnational in Palestinian Film Production -- tIII THE POLITICS OF MUSIC -- tLiberating Songs: Palestine Put to Music -- tDueling Nativities: Zehava Ben Sings Umm Kulthum -- tAgainst Hybridity: The Case of Enrico Macias/Gaston Ghrenassia -- tIV REGIONAL AND GLOBAL CIRCUITS -- t''First Contact'' and Other Israeli Fictions: Tourism, Globalization, and the Middle East Peace Process -- tProphecy, Politics, and the Popular: The Left Behind Series and Christian Evangelicalism's NewWorld Order -- tTelling Stories in Palestine: Comix Understanding and Narratives of Palestine-Israel -- tSentimentality and Redemption: The Rhetoric of Egyptian Pop Culture Intifada Solidarity -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis important volume rethinks the conventional parameters of Middle East studies through attention to popular cultural forms, producers, and communities of consumers. The volume has a broad historical scope, ranging from the late Ottoman period to the second Palestinian uprising, with a focus on cultural forms and processes in Israel, Palestine, and the refugee camps of the Arab Middle East. The contributors consider how Palestinian and Israeli popular culture influences and is influenced by political, economic, social, and historical processes in the region. At the same time, they follow the circulation of Palestinian and Israeli cultural commodities and imaginations across borders and checkpoints and within the global marketplace.The volume is interdisciplinary, including the work of anthropologists, historians, sociologists, political scientists, ethnomusicologists, and Americanist and literary studies scholars. Contributors examine popular music of the Palestinian resistance, ethno-racial "passing" in Israeli cinema, Arab-Jewish rock, Euro-Israeli tourism to the Arab Middle East, Internet communities in the Palestinian diaspora, café culture in early-twentieth-century Jerusalem, and more. Together, they suggest new ways of conceptualizing Palestinian and Israeli political culture.Contributors. Livia Alexander, Carol Bardenstein, Elliott Colla, Amy Horowitz, Laleh Khalili, Mary Layoun, Mark LeVine, Joseph Massad, Melani McAlister, Ilan Pappé, Rebecca L. Stein, Ted Swedenburg, Salim Tamari  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aArab-Israeli conflict. 0aPalestinian ArabsxSocial conditions. 0aPopular culturexPolitical aspectszPalestine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aHorowitz, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca